{"_type":"item","id":"019ea4fcc6877cc7ae826a5d56aec737","type":"discussion","status":"active","title":"Recut codetools skills around ephemeral-vs-durable: Basic (tiny scripts) vs Advanced (disciplined durable engineering)","description":"## Why this discussion\nHeavy owner+agent shaping of the recut codetools seeded skills (current scaffolds: minerva_codetools_coding / _advanced_coding / _plugin_authoring). The owner reviewed skill 1's content (via a Minerva note) and found it mis-framed. Capturing the philosophy here BEFORE filing the DCR + work_items to rewrite, so the reasoning stays attached to the resulting work. (Provenance for the eventual skill-rewrite DCR.)\n\n## The reframe (owner's note on skill 1)\nThe 'Coding' skill was built from a repo/codebase mental model (semantic index, locate symbols, navigate, buffered reviewable edits). That is the WRONG framing for the basic skill. Basic coding = tiny, throwaway, single-shot: 'write me Fibonacci / Hello-World / a quick transform' — write a small script (shell/Python/etc.), run it, read the output, hand back the result. Rarely >1000 lines, almost never a repo, no exploration, no index.\n\n## The clarifying axis: EPHEMERAL vs DURABLE\n- Basic = ephemeral: throwaway script, run it, return the answer. No tracking, no ceremony, no delegation, no repo. Optimized for speed.\n- Advanced = durable: real work that must survive and be trusted — so it is tracked (docket), done safely (risk discipline), scaled (sub-agents) when big.\nThis axis (not 'small vs large') is what makes docket/risks/sub-agents principled inclusions in Advanced rather than a grab-bag.\n\n## Decision: 3 skills, Advanced absorbs repo work (owner)\nBasic Coding (tiny scripts) / Advanced Coding (real-codebase: navigate + edit + debug + research + visualize + process discipline) / Plugin authoring. Keep 3 (no 4th). Manage Advanced's large surface with a MODAL system prompt (navigate/edit · debug · research · visualize · track-work · delegate), pin the union of tools, prompt gates when each mode fires.\n\n## Basic Coding — drafted rewrite\n- id: minerva_codetools_basic_coding (rename from _coding — TBD)\n- title: 'Basic coding — write, run, and return a small script'\n- summary: Quick, self-contained coding: write a short script, run it, return the result. One-off requests (function/calculation/Hello-World/Fibonacci). No repo, index, or exploration.\n- system_prompt: small self-contained coding to answer a concrete request; short script, rarely a repo; do NOT index/explore/navigate; loop = write file -> execute -> read output -> fix-and-rerun -> deliver; smallest thing that answers it; if it needs a real codebase, hand off to the larger codebase-coding mode (escalation phrased by CONDITION, not by sibling name — per owner's earlier C6 note 'skills shouldn't reference other skills directly').\n- preconditions: user wants a small standalone task now; no repo/index assumed.\n- outcome: small script written + executed; result verified + delivered; script left in editor.\n- steps: 0 scope+pick scratch path; 1 file_write; 2 bash to execute (capture stdout+stderr); 3 file_edit + rerun on error; 4 (opt) file_read outputs; 5 deliver.\n- tool_deps: file_write, file_edit, file_read, bash (down from 14). Dropped: stale_check, analyze, query, get_context, describe_symbol, grep, glob, get_diff, journal_mark. No validate, no cwd (use /tmp absolute paths).\n\n## Advanced Coding — the disciplined-engineering methodology (the meat)\nSystem prompt encodes a METHODOLOGY, not just tools. The loop:\n1. Frame — capture work in docket with a Definition of Done (the in/out contract).\n2. Survey before writing — RE-USE MAP (what to reuse, DRY mitigation) + FILE PRE-FACTOR (files you have vs need). Owner: these working artifacts go in small NOTES.\n3. Design — pseudo-code the algorithm first (in a small NOTE).\n4. Build — small scoped changes, reuse mapped seams, match surrounding style/quality.\n5. Verify — tests / validate / review diff.\n6. Land — commit WIPs (per-file git add, co-author trailer, branch hygiene); USER decides when to push; update docket state.\n- Risk discipline throughout: verify branch/HEAD before commit; firewall scope creep into NEW docket items (DoD must not silently grow); dup-check for DRY; never force-push / --no-verify.\n- PROPORTIONALITY guardrail (load-bearing): scale the discipline to the task — a typo fix skips notes/pseudo-code/docket; a multi-file feature gets the full loop. Otherwise the skill is bureaucratic.\n- Anchor in the owner's RUBRIC: durability > DRY > reliability > well-factored > readability > cost. The re-use map = DRY, pre-factor = well-factored, pseudo-code = reliability — the rubric applied before code exists.\n\n## Knowledge & tracking decision rules (Advanced must TEACH these)\nNOTES (immediate, this-task-only, small, discard after): pseudo-code, file pre-factor list, API research ('use X this way' for this change).\nDOCKET (outlives the task) — the test: 'needed only to finish this task?' -> note; 'useful after it ships?' -> docket. Pick the type:\n- shaping a problem/want with the user (philosophy, unsettled) -> discussion (active->resolved; on resolve, spawns+links the dcr/work_items — provenance). Rare; triggered by heavy dialogue or explicit user ask. (THIS item is an example.)\n- new design direction -> dcr\n- defined unit of work -> work_item / bug\n- root cause -> rca\n- reusable incantation/path/gotcha -> hint\n- how-a-subsystem-works reference -> kb\n- non-obvious realization -> insight\nAPI research example of the split: 'use X for this change' -> note; 'how library X actually works' (reusable) -> kb.\n\n## Docket-project decision rules (Advanced must TEACH these)\n- Default to master (a fresh user has only master).\n- On entering a codebase, look for an existing project FIRST: glob *.dct (often gitignored, e.g. Docs/<name>.dct) -> docket_project_list -> attach/use it instead of master. Surface which project ('Found project foo, tracking there').\n- New project = an ongoing, distinct body of work with its own backlog (not a one-off). Creating one is user-facing/structural -> PROPOSE, don't auto-create.\n- Applied live: codetools has NO own .dct (none in minerva-plugins); loaded projects = minerva-services(MIN,primary)/cad/minerva(MNR). Codetools history lives in minerva, so this discussion was filed there; graduating codetools to its own project is a separate proposable decision (would fragment lineage — deferred).\n\n## Decisions still open\n1. note-vs-docket test + type table — confirm shape (owner leaning yes).\n2. project creation = always ASK (vs auto when confident) — agent leans ask.\n3. rename Basic id _coding -> _basic_coding?\n4. sub-agents = DEFERRED to v1 (least-proven, heaviest tool pull); add after the rest is HITL'd.\n\n## Next (on resolution)\nLock Basic into codetools/manifest.json; draft Advanced's modal system prompt around the methodology above; update Advanced tool_deps to absorb repo-nav (stale_check/analyze/query/get_context/describe_symbol/grep/glob/get_diff/journal_mark/file_* + docket_* ) on top of inspect/get_graph/explore/research/viz. Then HITL each skill in focused chats. Spawns: a skill-rewrite DCR or work_items linked back to this discussion.","created_at":"2026-06-08T02:08:09","updated_at":"2026-06-08T03:32:18","priority":2,"tags":["codetools","discussion","shaping","skills","ux"]}
{"_type":"item","id":"019ea523295175f2b7e9a0005dfc2e78","type":"dcr","status":"proposed","title":"Plugins seed knowledge (kb/hint) alongside skills, referenced by stable key","description":"## Motivation\nSkills MUST be self-contained: a seeded skill cannot reference a docket item by id, because an end-user who installs the plugin may not have the project that item lives in (verified constraint, codetools skills recut). Today the only durable knowledge a plugin ships is its skills — install seeds manifest.skills[] only (PluginManager.install_plugin -> _seed_plugin_skills; no kb/hint/knowledge path exists, grep-confirmed). So all substrate depth has to be crammed inline into skill system_prompts, which bloats them and prevents the browsable/queryable/updatable knowledge layer the rest of docket provides.\n\n## Proposal\nAdd a manifest `knowledge[]` array (kb + hint types; possibly insight) seeded into the user docket on install, PARALLEL to skills[]. The seeding apparatus already generalizes — reuse the skills machinery:\n- PluginManager._seed_plugin_skills / _unseed_plugin_skills -> a knowledge equivalent.\n- PluginSkillRecord (per-item provenance: which plugin shipped it, pristine content for diff, customised flag) -> PluginKnowledgeRecord.\n- The seed-consent dialog (PluginSkillSeedDialog) -> include knowledge items.\n- Unseed-on-remove keeping user-customized items (the kept-ids pattern).\n\n## Key design decisions\n1. STABLE-KEY references. Seeded items get a fresh ULID per install, so a skill cannot reference a kb by id. Knowledge items carry a manifest-assigned stable `key` (docket items already have a `key` field); skills reference kbs by key, resolved at use-time. This keeps skills self-sufficient (the kb is browsable DEPTH, never a hard dependency) while letting them point to more.\n2. TARGET PROJECT. Where seeded knowledge lands — master (default), or a plugin-scoped/component-scoped project. Ties to the docket-project decisions (a fresh user has only master; codetools work now lives in the shared `plugins` project, component=codetools).\n3. LIFECYCLE parity with skills: re-seed on reinstall (reload != reinstall); keep user-edited items on remove; pristine-hash diff to detect upstream changes.\n4. SCOPE of types: kb + hint first (reference + actionable gotcha). insight/discussion likely out (those are author-side, not shippable).\n\n## Consequences\n- Skills stay lean + self-contained; plugins ship the full knowledge taxonomy we designed (kb = how a subsystem works; hint = reusable gotcha), not just skills.\n- The annotation-substrate extension knowledge (and the 7 plugin-substrate trap-families) could ship as kbs the plugin-authoring skill points to by key, instead of being fully inlined.\n\n## Non-goals\nNot changing the skills mechanism itself; not seeding work_items/bugs/dcrs (those are work, not shipped knowledge); not auto-creating projects (propose-don't-auto stands).\n\n## Provenance\nSpun out of the codetools skills-recut discussion (plugins:019ea4fcc687) while shaping the self-contained plugin-authoring skill. For v1 the plugin-authoring skill is self-contained (knowledge embedded inline); this DCR is the path to lift that depth into shipped, browsable kbs later.","created_at":"2026-06-08T02:50:05","updated_at":"2026-06-08T02:50:17","priority":3,"tags":["dcr","docket","knowledge","plugins","seeding","substrate"]}
